title: For Sale:  M84 Sniper Scope M1C M1D Garand M-84 Clear Glass
postcontent: Up for sale from my collection is a M84 sniper scope with serial number 26105. This scope was manufactured by Libby-Owens-Ford, has clear optics in original condition, and is complete with original rubber eyepiece and sunshade. It shows a few signs of being used (see photos), but has >90% bluing remaining. There are some small, light surface rust spots on the tube. Finish on the adjustment knob covers is a bit worn. There are some scratches that may be from an M1D mount, which is not abnormal in these 70 year-old scopes. Optics are very clear and bright with NO flecks or spots in the sight picture (see photo). There are no import marks, no major blemishes other than what is described above, and the adjustment covers snap closed just as they should (see photos: I always try to show the worst, but please email me with questions). As you all know, because of its rugged construction and waterproofing after extensive testing, the 2.5 power 7/8" tube diameter "Telescope M84" (originally designated the T134 during trials) was chosen in late 1945 by the US Army to replace the 2.75 power 3/4" tube Weaver 330c (including the M73B1 and M8 variants), 2.5 power 7/8" tube Lyman Alaskan variants (M73, M81 and M82) on 1903A4 and M1D sniper rifles, while the Alaskan scope was also used in the M81 and M82 configurations on M1C Garand sniper rifles (see my other auctions. This M84 has 5-digit Serial Number 26690, just right for M1C, M1D or 1903A4 sniper application. This particular scope is a lot cheaper than a $2,000+ M81 or M82 in similar condition and would serve well on a M1D, 1903A4 or M1 Garand or 03A3 sniper clone. I have lots of other vintage WWII and Korean War sniper scopes, rings and mounts, so email me with your needs.

title: For Sale:  Charter Arms undercover 38 Special, 2 inch, 5 Shot, Lightweight Snub, 1986 Production OD3825, Exc Combat Grips, Finish black. WILL SHIP IF NOT LOCAL!
postcontent: Charter Arms debuted its Undercover series in 1964. It was always competitive with Smith & Wesson’s Chief’s Special Revolvers, but with the Off Duty’s debut in 1986, got even more so. Here is my First Year Production Off Duty, late 1986 from its 860000 range serial number. It was given to me from my grandfather. Manufacturer was Charter Arms of Stratford CT, and clearly marked. Type is traditional double and single action pocket revolver with transfer bar internal safety device. Construction is steel inner barrel, cylinder, yoke, pin, hammer, trigger, main frame and internal parts combined with an alloy barrel shroud and grip frame. Caliber is .38 Smith & Wesson Special, with a 5 shot swingout cylinder. Finish is transitional semi gloss blue; by 1987 the Off Dutys had a matte blue finish. Barrel is one piece 2 inch eight groove 1:18 rifling, with classic early Charter exposed ejection rod. Sights are barrel integral red dot front, with frame integral fixed notch rear. Cylinder capacity is 5 rounds of .38 Smith & Wesson Special or .38 Special +P ammunition interchangeably. Trigger is .312 serrated face, with matching short serrated spur hammer. Grips are factory issue hard rubber, thin finger groove, manufactured by Sile of Italy for Charter Arms. Weight empty is 17 ounces, with center of gravity at the rear cylinder face. Surface detractions on this Off Duty are minimal, principally edge wear to the trigger guard. I have it recently appraised  they said almost mint condition owners quote "we appraise this Charter as Excellent, 90 percent vicinity by our estimate". Photos, at any rate, ought to suffice for our distinguished shoppers to judge finish grade for themselves. Bore, chamber, and mechanism are all bright and clean. Hammer travels an additional 5 degrees on all five positions on double action after the cylinder times. There is no lateral play to the cylinder with the trigger fully depressed. Double Action trigger pull is smooth 9 to 10 pound vicinity, with a crisp 5 pound original single action trigger pull. Cylinder face to forcing cone gap measures a perfect .006. We estimate this revolver has been fired fewer than 50 times. Bore, cylinder chambers and mechanism are all bright and clean. Similar revolvers from Taurus and Smith & Wesson command prices upwards of $500 apiece. However I'm selling mine for only $ 379.00 OBO.  payment is with USPS Money Order & Not Credit Card or western union. Any ammunition in my photos is Not included.
